Why some emails show MAPI and others show SMTP
1. It depends on how the email was submitted into Exchange

Even if everything is in the same Microsoft Exchange / Microsoft 365 environment, there are two different submission methods:

A) MAPI (Microsoft Outlook user submission)

Used when:

A user sends email from Outlook desktop or Outlook connected client
The mailbox is directly connected to Exchange

Flow:

Outlook submits the email using MAPI (Exchange-native protocol)
Exchange processes it and later converts it into SMTP for delivery

👉 This is why headers show:

X-ClientType: MAPI
Exchange organization headers (X-MS-Exchange-*)
User/mailbox context
B) SMTP (application or system submission)

Used when:

Email is sent from applications, servers, scripts, monitoring tools, or services
PowerShell, .NET apps, API-based systems, etc.

Flow:

System sends email using SMTP directly to Exchange or relay
Exchange treats it as a standard SMTP message from a service identity

👉 This is why headers show:

Standard Received: chain only
No MAPI client headers
Often service-based sender identity (e.g., noreply or system account)
2. Why both exist in the same organization

Because Exchange supports multiple entry channels:

Source type	Protocol used	Reason
Outlook users	MAPI	Rich mailbox-aware communication
Applications / servers	SMTP	Simple programmatic email delivery

They are not different systems — they are different entry points into the same mail platform.

3. Key point for leadership understanding

👉 This difference is not about internal vs external email
👉 It is not about different mail servers
👉 It is strictly about origin of email submission

4. Why this matters

This distinction helps explain:

Why headers differ between emails
Why some emails have richer Exchange metadata
Why system-generated emails look simpler
Why user emails carry full mailbox context
5. One-line executive summary

Emails appear as MAPI or SMTP based on how they enter Exchange: Outlook users submit via MAPI (client protocol), while applications and systems submit via SMTP (standard mail protocol), even though both ultimately pass through the same Exchange transport system.

